ative computer developed by the Trickle team, driven by Claude Code. Here are the key details:\n\n### Main Features:\n- **Browser-based Visual Desktop Environment**: Provides a cloud sandbox with 2 vCPU / 4GB RAM / 10GB SSD\n- **No Configuration Required**: Unlike OpenClaw/Clawdbot, it offers zero setup - no Docker, command line, or local installation needed\n- **170,000+ Skills Store**: Pre-installed with a vast ecosystem of skills for automation\n- **Agent Teams Support**: Integrates Claude Code's Agent Teams functionality with a user-friendly interface\n- **Capy Mail**: Email command interaction system\n- **Automated Scheduled Tasks**: Similar to Codex-style automation\n\n### Product Positioning:\n- Targeted at creators, independent developers, and knowledge workers who find OpenClaw \"too engineering-heavy\"\n- Transforms command-line tools into intuitive WYSIWYG graphical interfaces\n- Allows ordinary users to complete complex tasks like programming, writing, and data analysis through conversation\n\n### Notable Achievements:\n- **Topped Product Hunt Weekly Chart** (Feb 9-15, 2026)\n- Described as \"a Claude Code computer in a browser\"\n- Provides mobile-friendly web interface\n\n### User Experience:\nOne user reported testing Happycapy's integration with Moltbook (agent platform), where the AI demonstrated ethical boundaries by refusing to execute inappropriate commands, showing that \"the AI has its own bottom line.\"\n\n### Availability:\n- Free tier available\n- Website: happycapy.ai\n- Supports installation of custom skills and parallel execution of multiple skills\n\n---\n\n**Note**: The search results didn't return specific Reddit discussions about \"GitHub Agent HQ\" or \"Inspector\" from February 2026. The MCP Inspector mentioned in one result appears to be related to Model Context Protocol debugging rather than the specific context you're looking for.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
